@flexiarg peripherals/progress-heartbeat-distinct-from-cycle-completion
@title Progress Heartbeat Distinct From Cycle Completion
@sigils [💓/搏]
@audience peripheral designers, conductor implementers, watchdog authors
@tone foundational
@style pattern
@keywords heartbeat, watchdog, progress, cycle, silence, liveness, FM-regulator, tickle, multi-watcher, false-positive, false-negative
@references [peripherals/constrained-execution-envelope peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution peripherals/canonical-typed-event-vs-side-channel realtime/liveness-heartbeats realtime/loop-failure-signals]

! conclusion: A peripheral's "is it alive?" signal must be a progress heartbeat distinct from its cycle completion event. Conflating the two produces watchdogs that fire on healthy long-running cycles (false positives) and watchdogs that fail to fire on wedged cycles still inside their nominal duration (false negatives).

  + context: A peripheral has a cycle — a unit of work it opens, processes,
    and closes. A watchdog (or supervisor, or conductor, or operator) wants
    to know whether the peripheral is alive: making progress, or stuck.

  + IF:
    The peripheral's cycles can vary in legitimate duration (some take
    seconds, some take minutes), and the watchdog needs to distinguish
    "still working on it" from "wedged."

  + HOWEVER:
    The naive implementation uses cycle-open-duration as the liveness
    signal: if a cycle has been open longer than threshold T, the
    peripheral is "stuck." This conflates two different things:

    - **Cycle phase** (open / closed) — describes whether a unit of work
      is currently being processed.
    - **Progress liveness** — describes whether *anything* is happening
      inside the peripheral right now.

    A healthy peripheral can have a cycle open for 10 minutes while
    actively making progress every second. A wedged peripheral can
    silently freeze 5 seconds after opening a cycle and stay frozen until
    something kills it. Cycle-open-duration tells you neither.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - False-positive watchdog: long but legitimate cycles trip the
        watchdog. The watchdog kills healthy work. Operators learn to
        widen T, which widens the blind spot for real wedges.
      - False-negative watchdog: a cycle wedges 5 seconds in and stays
        wedged for the remaining 9:55 of its nominal duration. The
        watchdog fires "on time" — too late to help.
      - Heartbeat-as-pulse-without-content: the peripheral emits "I'm
        alive" pings with no payload. The watchdog can't tell whether
        the peripheral is alive AND making progress, or alive AND in
        a tight retry loop, or alive AND deadlocked-on-IO-waking-up.
      - Conductor-as-watchdog: a conductor that steps the peripheral
        forward AND watches it for liveness conflates the regulator
        and the supervisor. When the conductor wedges, the watchdog
        wedges with it.

  + THEN:
    Make the heartbeat first-class and distinct from the cycle:

    1. **Emit progress heartbeats from inside the work**, not from cycle
       boundaries. The heartbeat is "I just did a meaningful unit of
       work" — a file processed, a frame written, an event handled. The
       heartbeat is keyed on `:last-progress-at` (or similar) and is
       updated by the work itself, not by the supervisor.
    2. **Separate the heartbeat channel from the cycle channel**. Cycle
       start/end events carry "what work is this" semantics. Heartbeats
       carry "the work is moving" semantics. A watchdog subscribes to
       heartbeats; a UI subscribes to cycle events. (See:
       peripherals/split-transport-from-embodiment — heartbeats are a
       distinct transport concern.)
    3. **Watchdog measures real silence**, not cycle-open-duration.
       The watchdog fires when (now - :last-progress-at) exceeds T,
       regardless of which cycle is open or how long it has been open.
       Cycles that legitimately take 10 minutes are fine as long as
       they emit a heartbeat every few seconds.
    4. **Heartbeats carry a small payload** describing what just
       happened ("processed file X," "wrote frame N," "handled event
       type E"). This converts the heartbeat from a pulse into a
       diagnostic. When the watchdog fires, the last-heartbeat payload
       tells you what the peripheral was doing just before it wedged.
    5. **The regulator (conductor / FM stepper / tickle) is separate
       from the watchdog**. The regulator paces work forward. The
       watchdog detects silence. The two should be implemented as
       distinct processes, ideally with the watchdog supervising the
       regulator. (See: project_war_machine_as_tm_on_manifold for
       the regulator-as-head-of-TM framing.)

  + BECAUSE:
    The problem is fundamentally one of clock alignment. Cycle phase
    runs on a work-bounded clock (this cycle takes as long as the work
    takes). Liveness needs to run on a wall-clock or a tick-clock
    (silence is measured in seconds since something happened). Trying
    to use one clock for both produces the FM-regulator-vs-watchdog
    confusion: the regulator wants long cycles for big work; the
    watchdog wants short cycles for fast detection; they cannot both
    win on the same axis.

    The fix — separate channels for separate clocks — is the same
    pattern as feedback_perceived_time_dual_clock (agent memory): two
    clocks must be bridged through an explicit convolution, not papered
    over by treating one as the other. Heartbeats and cycle events are
    two clocks; the convolution is the watchdog's silence calculation.

    The pattern has an institutional reading too: peripheral cycles are
    glacial-loop events (M-cycle, M-mission, M-cycle-of-cycles). Progress
    heartbeats are social-loop events (something just happened). The
    distinction is the same as inhabitation-feeds-evolution's
    fast/slow split, applied to the liveness question.

    + evidence: multi-watcher fix (2026-05-24, codex-8): the watchdog
      was firing on healthy long-running cycles and failing to fire on
      cycles that wedged shortly after opening. Codex added an explicit
      `:last-progress-at` keyed on per-iteration work events; the
      watchdog was changed to measure real silence rather than
      cycle-open-duration. False positives dropped to zero; false
      negatives became detectable on the watchdog's own timescale.

    + evidence: realtime/liveness-heartbeats (futon3 pattern library):
      the realtime patterns already articulate the distinction at the
      transport layer. This pattern lifts the distinction into the
      peripheral-design layer and makes it a design-time decision, not
      a runtime emergent.

    + evidence: futon0 cron-jobs.edn (2026-05-23): the
      pattern-index-rebuild cron entry was added because the main work
      loop did not heartbeat its progress to a separate channel — the
      TSV file appeared "stale" because nothing was checking real
      silence on the index-rebuild work, only cycle-open-duration on
      the parent multi-watcher.

    + evidence: M-war-machine-pilot (futon3c, DERIVE 2026-05-24): the
      mission selected "Tickle v2 mechanical FM regulator" over
      "Tickle v1 watchdog" precisely because v1 conflated regulator and
      watchdog. v2's mechanical FM regulator paces forward; the
      watchdog is then layered on top measuring heartbeat silence,
      not regulator cycle-open-duration. This pattern formalises the
      reasoning.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - When designing any new peripheral with cycles, add a heartbeat
      schema to the transport layer at design time, not after the
      first watchdog false-positive incident.
    - Heartbeat payloads must be small but informative: at minimum
      timestamp + work-tag + counter. This is the same shape MUSN
      events use for tool-call telemetry.
    - Watchdog implementations must NEVER subscribe to cycle events
      for liveness. If a watchdog is found doing so, treat it as a
      latent incident regardless of current symptom status.
    - For M-war-machine-pilot specifically: the Tickle v2 conductor
      MUST be specified with a :last-progress-at heartbeat distinct
      from its cycle. The watchdog (whether bell-based, cron-based, or
      operator-pinged) subscribes to the heartbeat. This is the v0
      observer-stage contract.
    - Cross-link: peripherals/canonical-typed-event-vs-side-channel —
      the heartbeat should be a first-class event in the transport
      taxonomy, not a parallel ping channel.
